  splitter.
Description
  Use the OnSplitterDblClick event to respond to mouse double-clicks.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterClick

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseDown
Summary
  Occurs when the user presses a mouse button with the mouse pointer over the splitter.
Description
  Use the OnSplitterMouseDown event handler to implement any special processing that should occur as a
  result of pressing a mouse button.

  The OnSplitterMouseDown event handler can respond to left, right, or center mouse button presses and
  shift key plus mouse-button combinations. Shift keys are the Shift, Ctrl, and Alt keys. X and Y are
  the pixel coordinates of the mouse pointer in the client area of the Sender.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseMove, TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseUp

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseEnter
Summary
  Occurs when the mouse pointer moves over the splitter.
Description
  Write an OnSplitterMouseEnter event handler to take specific action when the user moves the mouse
  over the splitter.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseLeave

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseLeave
Summary
  Occurs when the mouse pointer moves off from over the splitter.
Description
  Write an OnSplitterMouseLeave event handler to take specific action when the user moves the mouse off
  the splitter. For example, you can use this event to undo changes that were made in an
  OnSplitterMouseEnter event handler.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseEnter

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseMove
Summary
  Occurs when the user moves the mouse pointer while the mouse pointer is over the splitter.
Description
  Use the OnSplitterMouseMove event handler to respond when the mouse pointer moves after the control
  has captured the mouse.

  Use the Shift parameter of the OnSplitterMouseMove event handler, to determine to the state of the
  shift keys and mouse buttons. Shift keys are the Shift, Ctrl, and Alt keys or shift key-mouse button
  combinations. X and Y are pixel coordinates of the new location of the mouse pointer in the client
  area of the Sender.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseDown, TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseUp

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseUp
Summary
  Occurs when the user releases a mouse button that was pressed with the mouse pointer over the
  splitter.
Description
  Use an OnSplitterMouseUp event handler to implement special processing when the user releases a mouse
  button.

  The OnSplitterMouseUp event handler can respond to left, right, or center mouse button presses and
  shift key plus mouse-button combinations. Shift keys are the Shift, Ctrl, and Alt keys. X and Y are
  the pixel coordinates of the mouse pointer in the client area of the Sender.
See Also
  TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseDown, TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMouseMove

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterMoved
Summary
  Occurs after the user has retiled the navigation pane using the splitter.
Description
  Write an OnSplitterMoved event handler to take specific action when the user finishes dragging the
  edge of the neighboring control using the splitter.
See Also
  OnCanResize

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@@TJvCustomNavigationPane.OnSplitterPaint
Summary
  Occurs when the splitter needs to draw itself.
Description
  Write an OnSplitterPaint event handler to customize the appearance of the splitter. For example, use
  an OnSplitterPaint event handler to give a splitter the appearance of the splitters that appear in
  cool bar objects. Use the Canvas property as a drawing surface for painting the splitter. Use the
  ClientRect property to determine the coordinates of the canvas on which to paint the splitter.

  When a splitter object receives a WM_PAINT message, it paints its background before generating the
  OnSplitterPaint event.

